              'Grade 4-5': 'Earl seems like a man stuck in a routine. He wipes the counter repeatedly and has been at the diner so long he doesn\'t notice the fan anymore. He hides his truck\'s rust from customers, showing he has some pride despite the diner\'s decline. The woman is mysterious — she is not from the area, wears a dress "too good for Rosie\'s," and reads the menu carefully. When she closes her eyes holding the coffee, it suggests she is tired or relieved. Earl asks "Passing through?" because "that was what you asked," showing he follows social scripts. Her answer "I haven\'t decided yet" is intriguing because it suggests she might stay, creating a sense of possibility.',
              'Grade 6-7': 'Earl is characterised through the rhythms of habitual action: wiping the counter "for the fourth time that hour," pouring coffee from thick white china — gestures so practised they have become automatic. His concealment of the truck\'s rust reveals a man aware of decline but managing its visibility, performing adequacy. He asks "Passing through?" not from curiosity but from script: "because that was what you asked." This meta-commentary on social ritual exposes the diner as a space governed by convention rather than genuine exchange. The woman, by contrast, disrupts every convention: her dress is "too good," her attention to the menu too careful, her presence too deliberate. She is characterised through what she withholds — her name, her origin, her purpose. The moment when she wraps "both hands around" the coffee and closes her eyes is psychologically dense: the writer offers three possible explanations — "gratitude or exhaustion or the particular relief of a person who has been driving for a very long time" — and refuses to choose between them, preserving her mystery. The exchange\'s final line — "I haven\'t decided yet" — transforms a polite enquiry into an existential declaration, suggesting that the decision about whether to stay involves more than this particular diner. The encounter is defined by its restraint: two strangers performing a recognisable ritual while something unspoken passes between them.',
